 Everything all right? Yes. Quite happy. I accept them as they come. And you can't do - can't do better than that with your fellow man. Mind you you can - you can be very very cross with your fellow man if he's not - not playing the game with you, you can
 
also - pull him to pieces and revile him, if it's necessary. At the same time if you - if he shows respect you must show him respect. And that is my approach to life. I'm just come down to try and classify these groups. Trying to get to the type of person
 
that - represents group - the middle class group which I more or less quoted just now. Those that tolerate - and - and accept. I think I'm trying to discriminate or make myself clear on that point, have I? But - now is there any question you was to ask ab
out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You're talking about a middle class group, what other class would there be, would there be a working man's group as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 There - there would - could be working man, could be white - they could be in a supervisory grade in some capacity lik
e that or they could be - shall we say - solicitors offices or - or that type of - or - what - what we - we used to describe as an ink slinger. Yes, you see because - because they - they had a - a sort of self-importance about them that you couldn't alway
s catch on to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Would they set themselves up above the ordinary working people do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Some would try. Some would try but when - when - when you can hold - hold your own with them and you always feel equal to them then they climb down you se
e. You see, you've got to do that, you've got to do that. I mean to say, no matter if you in rage you've got to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 There would be two main groups then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Two. Then - now I come to the more humble type. They are the ones you can always get on w
ith. He was the old cockney from London or whatever, you always got on with them you know. You got the right approach you get on - I always find them happy enough. And they're the people I like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You felt your own family was in between because of your father's activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
I think some of my family would be - on the snobbish side. I do. I feel my older brother would be. I don't say so much about younger brothers. Because - one has been in the Navy and he's roughed it in the Navy. The other}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid798420\charrsid2370612  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 one, G.P
.O., he was senior draughtsman with the G.P.O. in London when he retired. Only ten years ago. That's Reg. Alec, the youngest one, the youngest boy - I don't - haven't had sufficient dealings with these over the years you see to know because - well I - I s
u
ppose we could say, well we've held ourselves aloof - we haven't held ourselves aloof, we've had our family to bring up. My - my - my - my - I've been a - more of a misfortune rather a fortune inasmuch as I've had to go and seek work, where they'd had it 
always on the plag}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
e, it's there, it's always been there for them. They haven't had to go and look for it. We - which gives me a wider scope and a wider ability to speak on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You said that you touched your cap to people when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh 
yes. Yes, yes, yes, yes. I think - it's a - it's what should be done - in respect to your elders or to - or to the lady. It's never done these days or very rarely although if you meet an elderly man who's been brought up in an atmosphere, I'm with my wife
, first thing he does is to lift his - if he's wearing a hat he'll lift his hat. I've had that happen to us very recently on several occasions you know. And it's a pleasant feeling you know, to feel there's still some of those people about. It's so rare.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When you were a boy it was mostly to your elder and ladies, there weren't particular kinds of people that you had to lift your cap to?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh - well, school yes, schoolmasters, they all expected you to do that didn't they oh you won't know, but they did. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Anyone else outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well I suppose you would to - the parson. I think you would. Another open question
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was there anyone you called sir when you were a child, or master, did you use those kinds of words to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I don't quite follow you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You said you touched your cap to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you call people sir, did you used the expression?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Sir - yes, because even - even - mostly to - much as I didn't want to do it, right up to the last I had to sir so
me people. Because it was - I was an under employee. I - I'll put it this way, they were in a higher category. There was the Admiral you see of the yard I - to talk - when he gave me my I.S.M. - thank you sir, you know. I accepted my Imperial Service Meda
l
 and thanked him and - no - but it went very much against the grain in some respects, I thought I was humbling myself, and I did - I did quite a few times, I - I - I often thought - I went on various - conferences with my bosses down the various dockyards
, like Devonport and up to - up to - Ports - down - down to Portsmouth from Chatham and also to the Admiralty and I had to - I had - people were head of me who were sir - being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 stirred}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612  by people above me so I more or less had to, you know, be a bit diplomatic and say sir. But it went against the grain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was there anyone outside the work situation who you'd say sir to? Were there any local dignitaries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, I think I would treat them - all depending which way - in which manner I said; sir. I say it's
 something you can be very very - what can I say - emphatic in saying sir, mean to empl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 y a little degree of wrath doesn't it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where you lived in Portsmouth, who were considered the most important people in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well - important people - o
f course important people as far as - who was - now you going back to when I was young. I suppose - the important people in my life were mother and father. That's perfectly obvious. See. But within the community a large I suppose in my - my grandparents o
n the Isle of Wight were important to me because they gave me satisfaction and - personal satisfaction in holidays and - I suppose - other than that, nobody more important than myself. I was quite - I was quite - quite important in myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I'm thinking more in a social sphere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
No. No. I don't - there weren't that local - there were no local heroes in - inasmuch that - a certain crowd who played for Portsmouth at the time in the football team, Billy Smith and Stevie Smith, they were rather short of
 it, I can remember one - one had moustache, Stevie he was short and bandy, of course they - their football shorts came down below their knee in those days you know and - and Stevie, always together they were, and Stevie was about couple of feet taller, a
ppeared to be to me you know and he was plain clean shaven. Now they were always together like Mutt and Jeff, you know. But - I suppose we looked upon them as important people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Who would your father have respected, who would he have thought was grand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Well I don't know. I expect he saw himself - I'm as good as they are, same sort - same thought as I would have these days. Yes, I would say following his dogmatic manner you see. If he was right or if he thought he was right even he'd fight it to the
 last ditch. He would really, whether - whether - whether it's the reigning monarch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, now, I have to wander around a bit in my mind in that respect. We meet - we
 meet them don't we, these - these - we meet them often. They may - they may not be the type of people one would associate with but at the same time they can be as you say, the real lady and real gentleman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Can you remember any individuals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, 
no, I see what you're getting at. Yes, I think of one now who worked I believe or was - a civil servant and he was my Bible class teacher. Saoge Ope his name, I have a book, one of Dickens books, Barnaby Rudge, that he gave me from his Bible class and he 
w
as our Bible class teacher, elderly man, very elderly man. Been a - been in the Indian civil service and he gave us - gave me this on Christ as a present - Christmas present. I've got his signature and all and I've still it and - he was what I called a pe
rfect gentleman. He was so gentle. He was strict with his gentleness mind you but he was a perfect gentleman in his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 manners}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
 his approach to us boys, well, young men, we were teenagers. This is at Emmanuel church where I told you I eventually went in the cho
ir you know. Yes. That - that's why - why - that's only one example but - there were so many of them about you see that I forget. But that - that is one particular person who would - yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was there any difference between the kind of people that went to church and the kind of people who went to a chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Oh I - I - you know, I've always had very perverse feelings about this inasmuch as in - I always thought a Wesleyan - since I have two pictures you see, I always thought the Wesleyan was a B
ible thumping crowd. No, that's - that's to be perfectly candid. Always thought they were Bible thumping crowd, always - it's always stand outside the chapel after chapel and talking, you know, all this - you've seen it. Yes. And I always felt it you know
. But it didn't seem it the Church of England. Very rarely see it outside Church of England. Might - they might have foregathered in the - in the porch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 -way and had a little conf}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 ab with the vicar as they came out but - but you wouldn't see them standing outside like they do - you know that's my - that's my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Would you say that the kind of people who went to church were more middle class than the kind of people who went to chapel or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well in a varying degree I would say more middle class. Yes. O
f course you have this - this factor entering into - being a - being a state church as it is, the Church of England I'm referring to of course, the established church, you would have a small number of regular church goers who were looked upon as essential
 
to the upkeep of the church. In other words they - they - fill the platter very well in other - in more ways than one, you know, they were called upon in more ways than one to do jobs so far as the church was concerned, I mean from financial assistance an
d also their ability to contact other people who could do things as well. I say yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 More so than chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes I think so. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where you lived - you remember Plymouth more clearly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, I do, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did all the people in your position in life have the same standard of living round where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 On the whole, yes. On the whole, yes, I would say so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 There weren't any groups who were very badly off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 An now wait a minute. Now - you're coming back to something which h
as come into my mind - we're speaking about it I believe to Michael and Joan yesterday, where people used to take the family and the father's dinner down to the gate. Did I tell was it you? Were you hear when I - did I tell you that or - oh, yes, yes, wel
l
 that was a fact. I thought - oh well - there was certainly people pretty - pretty badly off, there's no doubt about that. Then of course, their circumstances could be caused by two factors. Too large a family or too fond of drink. That's what I would - I
 put it down - or inability to - to understand economics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So there were these poorer groups then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh - yes, I would say there were poorer groups, yes. Yes, looking back on things I say there were. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Can you describe a family that you knew that were badly off who lived near you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
What, in those days? Of course you see, I'm in an unfortunate position in answering this questions that I'm - I was the child of a father who was progressive, in other words, he was going up and up. Therefore 
- as I was growing older and could appreciate this particular way of life if would appear than I'm growing away from perhaps that scale of - of human being that - were really - because you know, appearances are not always what they are. I - I'll put it li
k
e this, we know very well that - there are certain types of individuals who's got plenty of means of keeping themselves decent, they've got it, they haven't - they haven't got rid of it they haven't drunk it away, they haven't thrown it away, they've stil
l
 go it but they prefer to live the life they live rather than - rather than anything else. It's a life of choice with some of them so therefore you - if you can - if you can manage a family into that category they live by choice - I'm thinking of people l
i
ving in caravans in those days who lived by choice in a caravan, roaming the countryside for instance, what we call diddycoys. Now you - they're not the true Romany kind of people, they are of a gipsy type who road - roam areas, they travel from farm to f
arm or pick fruit and that sort of thing and - they set up little communities in areas, in these I suppose the - half these - these merchants you see around, they call them }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 gypsies}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 , they're not more gipsies than you or I because - they come through from tha
t scale of life which was a Romany life of gipsy life to come on the dregs of - from a town. Normal ordinary life, and they choose that type of life because it's the easiest way out, they haven't got to be clean, they haven't got to - they haven't got to 
- buy anything, they can steal it if they want to. And I - I'm talking from a knowledge of these people that we had a camp quite near to us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you know of these people before the first war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I - I - no, well I would say that these same type of 
people persisted. I'm thinking now of Milton, round Milton Shores which was something like the tidal river down here at Wivenhoe but mud - plenty of mud flats. They lived in old shacks right on the river bank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You remember them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I do remember th
em 'cos we used to go round - my father used to take us round - round these shores for a walk on a Sunday afternoon, they used to have some awful dogs you know, like - well they're like prairie dogs you know - scavenging for food and - that's the type of 
individual I really mean. I do - I do feel that they are the - the type of people that are not poor. They're not poor you see. They're only poor to us. But - you know, I - I really they're much - much more - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid798420\charrsid2370612 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 nriched enriched in this respect, that - they can live on nothing. Without working for it I've seen them go from door to door and pick it up you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did they ask for help from people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh well, they didn't ask for help, now that's a wrong way of putting it. They came - womenfolk - came with 
