Mostly - people I met subsequently, rather than school - either school - I mean like schoolboys that - or school - fellow - fellow schoolboys - went in the services and - oh dear, anyhow, life was passed in between ages. But I ha
ve many many of them, well I met quite a few of them since - I met one up in Invergordo when I was based up there during the first world war. I was surprised to see the person come up with two rings on his arm, walking up behind a - Admiral - oh dear oh d
e
ar, had the - Iron Duke at the time, not Beatty. No, no. No. Anyway, that's how I - I - I just can't think of the name, not Beatty, but anyway, I was just - seeing him walking on this floating dockside with - we'd - docked the ship in dock, she'd had a - 
c
ollision with one of our own craft, and - I looked at him, I said, Vic - Vic Shepherd, you know, he was a Naval constructor, he rose to be - knighted. Yes, he was a - head - Naval - Naval con - he was the Director of Naval construction, eventually when he
 retired - about the same time as I retired. And we used to - I - but - people like that you know. But - other than that - in the main - I - I was treading fresh water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, I - I didn't - embrace any
body particularly. Well - you know, a young Cornish fellow that used to live a few doors from me, we often used to go out together, but that was about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Out in the country. Because he was a - he was - more or less - of similar nature to myself in that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Oh they would come and see them, yes, they - would come in. They were welcome we always used to meet more or less - you know - at different functions that's why.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have to be in by any certain time when you'd left school and started work or were there no restrictions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well - I think really - we - were supposed to be in by - by not later than ten o'clock, we used - but we used to be in a bit earlier. I kno
w I - I very rare later than about - between nine and ten. But - of course, my father as I say being a public man like he was - he was a - he was always engaged elsewhere, with different - societies, all sorts of things like that. Politics and - other thi
ngs besides.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you go out with him before you joined the Imperial Constitution?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Well - well - oh you've got in the earlier stages where we used to go out with children, he used to take us round Portsmouth, round the - shore at Portsmouth, 'cos 
that's where I was born you see. But other than that - no, I - I don't think so. Because if there was anything - like any - gala or anything like that on, then - we'd all go together, mother and father and - so many other - members of the family, but othe
r than that - he was - as I say, too busy a man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you interest yourself in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
No, I - I - I - I - re - remained and still am a free agent. To be - he - he was a - take us for - or arrange for us to go, of course he was a - a man of - at
hletics as well you see, and he was Kent County three A's holdership for the Kent County when - when he - right up 'til the day he died, and he was seventy-six age of seventy-six. And - he organized - sports in the county from - what was - this was a very
 
professional run county, and he changed it over - right practically all - right over to amateurism, because he was a strong amateur man. And of course we joined in with it, in our way. I was a - I - I used to run cross country. I have tried the mile and h
alf mile but - ten miles - my mark rather than - than short runs, yes. I prefer long races, I used to do cross country a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you. Well it's a little bit enjoyable in the winter isn't it, you know, when you can get out there, especially running aga
inst - against the snow and hail you know. Oh it is, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I like walking now, I don't do any running much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh well we - the wife and I, we walked miles, and mind you we still walk miles about. I haven't got a car so I always walk where
ver I'm going.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Neither have we. We - I - I wouldn't give a thank you for that. But - of course the - you - you'll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5785297\charrsid2370612 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 ave gathered by now that - I - I've got a - a roving nature in that respect. But I - I see - what's good in nature. I like - I love ab
out the countryside, I love it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So what age were you when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Let's see. 1915, I was twenty-three the day before I was married, I was twenty three - the day before I was married, 1915.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You have two celebrations straight after each other each year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Wedding one day and - birthday the next, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How long had you known your wife then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 We got engaged - on her twenty-first birthday in - December '14. The beginning of December '14.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That was when you were engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How long had you known her before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh not very much. Not many months before that. I suppose about - five or six months perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So it was about a year before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How did you meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Well we - in those days of course there weren't - the cinema and that sort of thing that people want to go to - none of that, Sunday nights was a training night Had a general - general - for young people parade you know, and you would - well if you s
aw - saw a nice young lady, you know, give her the glad eye and that so of thing, but - then that was - that's - that's the general - you know, good evening, how are you you know. But if they - simply - shrug their shoulders, you know, they don't want it 
you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You met her on one of these parading evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Yes, along - it - it was - after church on Sunday evening. I remember quite well. I took her home of course. For company of course, saw her across the lines to Gillingham and that was that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 This would be up in Gillingham wouldn't it, I was thinking of Plymouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. No, no, it was Gillingham there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So you'd only been in Gillingham about two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I arrived October '12 to December '14, that's two years about. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you save up money for getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Oh - I did. I - I - I volunteered, 'cos war - war broke out August the fourth fourth - 1914. The wife and I - we were courting then. We were at Gravesend on that occasion when we heard the news. And - so - 
I - was - immediately transferred - I didn't finish my apprenticeship actually, I - I had five weeks go. No, six weeks to go - when they gave - I had instructions for us older boys - who - you know, to go into the dockyard, they were wanted, for the - for
 
repairing the - war dam - 2ar damaged ships coming in you see. As it was - well it had been - you know, seen a little action in the channel - off Dover and that, they were bringing them in the dockyard for repair and they want all - all the people they co
u
ld get. So I was more or less - pushed into that. Well after a few months in the - in the - following May, that was Aug - August '14, in the May - following - I vol - volunteered for service wherever they liked to send me and they sent me up to - Na - Nav
al base at Invergordon. And I stopped there. And that's where -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 But you actually got married in Gillingham?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So - I actually got married in Gillingham but I was - I was - up there three months and came down on the Friday or Saturday - took - well 
from Midday Friday got down here Saturday midday, and got married on the Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have to go straight back up again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No. No, we had - we had - I had seven days leave. And - went on a - sort of honeymoon down to - Ryegate. And then - I - I
 - we went back to Scotland - took her back because I went back to Scotland and went back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Had you got anywhere to go to arranged beforehand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh yes, yes, yes. Crofters cottage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was it Inverness way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh north of Inverness. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So after your marriage you went back to Scotland? Did your parents help - you in setting up a home or was it all off your own bat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh no, we didn't have a - when we went up Scotland we didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 But did your parents help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh lord no
. No. No, I went off on my own bat. Didn't we love. We did. Oh no, I - I - I went - when I - I was the first one to break away from home you see, and - we went up there and - we made our little bit of home - well, we didn't make a home, we had furnished a
ccommodation. Rough as it was, we had furnished accommodation. Well then - about - a bit later stage the wife had to come down - we were - expecting with our family coming along and - and I stopped only there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How long was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well - well 
it was about - I came down in the June didn't I. Well - the battle of Jutland wasn't it. Because I'd only just come home, was going up Railway Street Chatham when - I said, good God. And we saw that on the headlines - various ship had been sunk and that y
o
u know in the battle of Jutland. I couldn't - couldn't imagine it because I'd just been working on one or two of them. Great things you know, couldn't imagine them being sunk. Well we did see - the wife and I both saw one of the ships sunk up there, we we
re about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was this the one with all the children aboard having a party or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, yes, oh you've got that there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Our wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, your wedding. How many guests and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh, good Lord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was it a big wedding or a small wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
No, on a Sunday you see, midday - a little after midday service. We were married by - a blind vicar, Cannon Robyns, a blind vicar, he married us. And I think we were the last marriag
e he conducted - before he retired. I - my - my wife's father at that time had been in the choir there for about sixty years, no fifty sixty wasn't it, as a boy and man wasn't it, and - this was - the whole choir remained behind after service and gave us 
- you know, the full - full choral service. So we had - you know, quite a happy - send off from the church itself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have a reception?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 We had a small reception indoors, because - at that time - there weren't things around like there were -
 like there are these days you know. Expect to have a hotel reception, the wife sort of thing couldn't have that, not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you go back to your wife's home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh yes, went back to the wife's house - wife's house and had our re - reception. And
 - when - at the - well - we - about four o'clock in the afternoon we - went to - went off to our little honeymoon didn't we dear. Down to Ryegate, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When you went back to Scotland how long did you live in the crofter's cottage, did you come back to Gillingham after the first world war?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Oh, yes, I would say I - I - I packed up - returned to Chatham. You see. Well when the baby was born, our eldest boy was born, I returned to Chatham. And the of course the - started looking round to set up a ho
me you see. Which we eventually did after a - after several - about two month wasn't it. Two to three month. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did your wife have a job when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No. No. No. Old fashioned idea - that - oh you had a job when - when I - when - when we 
were - you gave up your job just before we married, all right. And from then on - she was housewife. Up 'til now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Before you got married what was your job?
\par <subject2>Mrs W. My job? Well - I don't know what you'd call it. I worked in an office It was a builders and an undertakers, and I was in there for five years before we were married.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 And you didn't continue working after marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh no, no, no. No. No. No, I mean - it - it wasn't thought of in those days really you see. Not - 
not for people to work after they married. Well I say the breadwinner was the man and he had to - it was his responsibility. And always maintained that, I still maintain it, because I - I think - in case of where there - where there are two people in the 
h
ouse, the man and the wife, in they've got a family at all, then they - all - all right for women's lib I know but - my - my point of view is that - the home should be the first consideration. I know - I know - what people think but I think myself that - 
i
t's - the cause of a lot of discontent in the present day - day and age, is the fact that the two people are out earning, and they have to get what they can get - to keep home, they don't want to keep home, they want to keep up with the Jones's. We were f
ar far happier in those days than they are now. Weren't we?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you like your job at the undertakers before?
\par <subject2>Mrs. We. Oh yes. Oh yes.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr. W. Long hours you know. I know I used to sometimes - eight o'clock in the evening. Yes
, eight o'clock in the evening I've - I've come down here haven't I. Hung around.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When was the first child born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, May 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Were any other children born before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, one - one born in 1918, yes. Our oldest girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So that would be two, did you have any more after 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Yes. One was born while I was out in India, 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How many children in all have you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 We've got - we've got - four - six children. Four boys and two girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Were your children born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, all born at home, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have any medical help during this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh well, you - the - the - midwife wasn't it, midwife made - and doctor wasn't in.
\par <subject2>Mrs. We. I had the doctor for - two of them I think. That's all, then I had the midwife - or a nurse.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr. W. Yes, they called them nurse in those days, they're called midwives today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you help in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Me, I was away from three of the births. I was away at the time our fi
rst one was born, I was still up in Scotland you see. When the third one was born I was in India in Bombay. When the last one was born I was out in Bermuda.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You say you had a midwife, did you have a nurse as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Well, no, a midwife was a nurse. They - they - they - she - she did they two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How long was the midwife around for, was she there just for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. You know more about it than I do I think.
\par <subject2>Mrs. W. Yes, of course I do. Well, no, she came in morning and night, and I have someone in during the day to do the work. That was for a fortnight.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That was a different woman, not the same woman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, no, same - a - well, the - the same woman came morning and night and the other one came during the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Two different women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You were in bed for a fortnight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, not for the whole fort - about seven days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have any relatives or neighbours to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No. No. Well I had a sister - who used to come up oc
casionally but - I mean they all had their own homes. And - and I had no neighbours that I could call on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You know all the questions the first time around about your own childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 These are to do with your own children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 My own, yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How much of your earnings would you give to your wife at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Cor lumme. I think I - yes, I was going to say - I - about - how much?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Very nearly all I suppose.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. Yes, I expect so. I say - at that time I suppose I was earning about thirty-three boab a week wasn't it when we first married.
\par 
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. I don't really quite remember.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. Yes, thirty - thirty-three. Then of course there was overtime and that sort 
of thing which - there - there wasn't a - yes, that's right, thirty-three and six. So - there wasn't a great deal by the time you paid your rent and that some of thing. But - of course - as the war progressed, and we - were going back now Going back now t
o
 1914/18. As the war progressed - overtime, all night work and all that sort of thing, you know, rush jobs, you - you got extra money. Well the sort of thing would naturally - give you - an income, and they also bought - bought forward what they called a 
w
ar bonus. And this war bonus - continued after the war for a - for a period, I - forget how long, it wasn't for - all the long. And then they - cut it off like that. So you - these days if they did that they'd all - all walk out wouldn't they? But - we - 
h
ad to take that because that was - that was a - a recognised deal, the war bonus, so therefore - therefore it was no longer required when you went back into peacetime. It wasn't absorbed into a - into the wages - as things were. Although incomes were goin
g
 up slightly. See you didn't drop right back to the thirty-three and six at the - outbreak of war, then onto - four or five pounds or whatever it might have been - with - including overtime perhaps and - that sort of thing, but of course - you were in a c
h
anging world. And incidentally you're getting into the world of unemployment. You see. And this - this - you have to get the axe - did apply, and I was one of those that - which altered in a way, because in 1919 I got my notice - to - to leave you know, I
 
got a discharge notice, and of course they could just give a fortnight's notice, two weeks, for you to - you know, have a look round. Well, I immediately - I got mine - I got a - I went straight over to Shorts at Rochester and got a start there - the foll
owing morning. So while that not - notice was in vogue - I was working. But - five days after they is}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
ued that notice they cancelled them all. So those who were out of work through that notice went back in the dockyard. I didn't. I hung on my fortnight the 
Then - the - they decided they wouldn't issue - the notices would not be - were were all void, and therefore - I could - come back. So I put in for a week's special leave - from the dockyard. I was working for Shorts. So I stopped a Shorts for three weeks
.
 And in that time - I - felt like that you know. Am I doing right or wrong, will they eventually issue - reissue these - and I'm in employment. So what I did was - I came back into dockyard after the end of the three weeks, and whilst I was back in I was 
l
ooking around for - for more substantial employment, you know, outside the sphere of the dockyard. I tried for - Metropolitan police, I tried for several other things, I tried for - a - a - a ship's carpenter's job, which I eventually got. But I - I took 
a
 ship the was already in the dockyard, a merchant ship, a - a - ex-German, bought some Russian refugees to Chatham - or to - to London, and she come round to Chatham for refitting. And I - when she - when she sailed I signed on her and went - went out eas
t trooping. That's how - that's how that came about. That's the reason why - our third child was born - while I was out in India.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Let's go back to when you just got married and you lived in this crofter's hut in Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was that a very big house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Good God. Don't say. My wife has never - never forgiven me for taking her up there like that. You know, the crofters cottage was about - walls about two foot thick, you know, and it was only like a bungalow, a stone - stone bungalow in 
- affair. It was a - a room and a bit, and mother earth was the floor, no floors there. Mother earth with a - a canvas covering, like - like lino - wasn't lino those days, it was - simply a canvas covering wasn't it dear. We had the best room in the house
,
 in the - in the croft, this croft, we had. The old people - lived in the other - we had one half and the old people had the other. We had - we had a - this living room, and a bedroom. The bedroom you just about get round like that wasn't it. No - no pipe
d water, we had to go outside - and use the - a village pump, and pump up water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 This would be only a sort of a temporary arrangement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I think we ought to bring it to the house you go in in the Kent area, because that was probably mo
re relative to the questions about family life inside the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
I think it would be better to take the Kent home which is when you had the first child rather than the one in Scotland which is just makeshift anyway. Was this in Gillingham or in Chatham, this first home you had down here?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Well we lived in Gillingham first.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. Yes. That's right. That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How long were you in the Gillingham home for?
\par <subject2>Mrs W. About seventeen and a half years. But we were in a - other - in Grain - in Grove - what do you call it - what's - what' was the name of that?</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. Granville Road. Granville Road. We were there eighteen months, but then we had to get out because - it was a reserv
ed house, it belonged to - a man - who was the official turn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 oo
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 k in the dockyard, and he was just on the point of retiring. And as he would want his home when he retired, we had to get out. Matter of fact I had to go to court over it, because I - I - we c
ouldn't find a place and that was that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When was this, was this very early on or was this later, Granville Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That was the - the - our first real home wasn't. That's our first real home.
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. How old was Colin when we went there? About three months?</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mr.W. No. Yes. Yes, he was wasn't, yes, I was - I was forgetting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was Colin the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. He would be about three months old when we went there. Yes, I suppose would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 So you were in Granville Road for eighteen months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have any relatives or lodgers living there with you or was it just the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, no, just our family. No, we had - yes, yes all right, yes. We had - we had we had three soldiers billeted on. Yes. And my - 
my wife and a young baby and with three soldiers billeted on us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That was a compulsory thing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Compulsory, oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have much room to cater for three soldiers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, we hadn't.
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. No, we only had to sleep them - didn't we, only had to sleep them.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You didn't have to give them food or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, no, no. No, went to bed and we - we - wouldn't see 'em go out in the morning without a cup of tea and something to eat, could we. I say
, I went to work, but they - they were - billeted on - on the - troops - troops place round - not billeted, that was their training ground and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have any paid help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Or anyone to do the washing for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh no, no. No, we wanted paying ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did either of you make or mend the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 mother - mother - you see what mother does now, she's been doing this all - all her married life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How about shoes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well I
 used to do - I used to do that. I used to repair the shoes. Right up right up - when they were - pretty well grown didn't I. Do all the shoe repair Other than stitching, I couldn't do stitching but - I used to put soles on them and heel - heel and sole t
hem.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How about helping around the house, did you do anything like cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Well I suppose I - I did - a little occasionally same as I - as was necessary, I'll put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How about cleaning or decorating, things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh yes, I - I did - I've done this house right out, you know, all - all the - same as now and I used to do it then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Making the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 There's one of my efforts today. That - that was always my - more or less, wasn't it, except - except during the - I s
uppose - when I was away from home of course my wife had to do it herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How about helping with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 We took our children out with us whenever we went. Didn't we dear? And they've all - all appreciated it, even our daughter's only a -
 was it - what - a few months ago, said to mum she said, do you remember, mum, when we used to go over to - to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 Up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13982660\charrsid2370612 nor}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 , across the water, take a - take a pie over there you know, straight out of the oven. A - a rabbit pie and a blackberry tart, all warm and 
go down and catch the boat across the river and go over in the woods over there and - we - well now she - she's - she's a woman with her own grandchildren. She said, how we used to enjoy it. We used to go round the countryside, and - as I told you earlier
 on we walked miles and miles, hundreds of miles and the children have walked miles and miles with us, haven't they dear, in their turn. As they've come along. Yes, we've - we've always taken them out with us. And I -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you ever do anything like reading stories to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Mother did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. I - I - I don't think I really did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you ever look after the children when your wife was away or out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh well - we - naturally I would. Naturally. Yes. But that - that was - hardly ever arose - did it dear. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did the children have any household tasks that they were allotted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh - yes. The girls were weren't they dear, they used - give a - well, they wasn't allo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 ed, they used to - naturally fall in line to - do a l
ittle bit. When the youngsters were young. Yes, when the - elder ones were able to help with the younger ones. Molly was nice - a nice little housema}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12544460\charrsid2370612 id one time was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 ' she dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 What time did the children go to bed in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Oh - round about - half past six. The younger ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When they were young, up to about ten?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Well, about half past seven I should think. In fact I know that the youngest boy, when he was quite a little boy, used to sit in his high chair to have his tea,
 he'd sit there and as soon as the six o'clock pips went on the wireless - he'd - so he used to go at six, and he was - about two to two and a half.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did they put themselves to bed?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Oh no. I always went up with them until they were - oh they -</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did the children share a bed or did they have their own bedroom?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Oh yes, they had to.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How many rooms were there in the house in Granville Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 In Granville Road - three bedrooms wasn't it. Three bedrooms. Yes, there, - there was only child, that's so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you have a bathroom in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No. No. No, not at Granville. Up on the top one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 That was after eighteen months you went to there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 We - that was 1918 - we moved up to - the top road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 And you had a bathroom up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, we had a bathroom up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When would the children have clean clothes?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. What questions, every week. Or - or - as often as they wanted them when they were tiny of course, always clean.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where would the meals be eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Well in the living room. It was our living room wasn't it? Like the one in there you see, this'll be the kitchen, middle room - scullery out there, you see scullery, kitchen, living room and the - what they term these days the lounge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where did your wife cook?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. In the kitchen.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 What kind of cooking equipment was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 A range. There was a gas cooker there wasn't it? Oh we - didn't we have - no we had a range there. Had a range. Yes, a cooking range. Coal.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When was breakfast eaten, what time of day?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. When we got there. Well - I don't know, half past eight. It - well it was according to - a - according to the age of the
 children, I mean when they had to go to school breakfast'd be about eight o'clock. To get them off about half past eight.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Would everybody be there then?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. Yes. But not father. Father'd be at work.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 You'd be at work would you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I would, yes. Yes. Used to start work at seven those days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How did you manage for your first meal?
\par <subject2>Mrs.W. How did father manage for his first meal? I don't know, I was in bed. Mr.W. Me - I - I expect I managed al
l right, must have done because I - I'm still here. No, I mean to say - no, I could - I always - I'm always able to look after myself in that respect aren't I? Always have been. I say - I - I - even now I come down and - cook my - porridge - after having 
a
 cup of tea in bed, I come down and then mother comes down and cooks the breakfast. So - and that's in those days the same thing used to happen, I used to cook myself something, if there was something to - if I wanted something cooked. Otherwise - I'd mak
e myself a - sandwich of cooked bacon and - you know - take with me. If - if there was any bacon, if I - we could afford it at that that time.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How about midday, would you stay at work midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No. No, I used to come home didn't I. I used to come home in those days, I used to cycle. Cycle home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 What kind of things would you eat midday? And would the children be home?
\par <subject2>Mrs. W. Yes. Yes, all together. Meat and veg. Meat and veg. That's all I can tell you.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you ever make bread or jam or pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No, very rarely. You made jam, yes, jam, yes, make - pounds and pounds of blackberry jam. Yes, and plum. Yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you do vegetables and fruits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 I grew - I used to grow vegetables at an allotment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Was there any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit around then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Well, tinned wasn't - tinned vegetables weren't known in those days. They weren't known. Dried vegetables - very very few dried vegetables, haricot beans, peas and that's all - tha
t's about - in the main wasn't it, the rest would be - normal - normal grown stuff you know, no tinned stuff like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How many days a week would you say you ate meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 How many days? Well I - I suppose so. I would say - of course you've got to take into consideration that - you could get - meat and meat.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When you were an improver you went to work at six o'clock in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes, six o'clock in the morning, and I used to come from Cleave Road up here at the top, walk right down Sou
thern Hill, through Chatham High Street, Rochester High Street to that place. At eight o'clock we went to breakfast, half an hour's breakfast, eight 'til half past, then we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Where would you have that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Come - come outside and sit on the wall of 
the pub there. Anyway, yes, anyway - or - or sit on our workbenches you know, and have a cup of tea and a - and a - whatever you had to eat, and then carry on then 'til twelve o'clock. Twelve 'til one for dinner, then one 'til five or half past five, I'm 
n
ot quite - I don't quite remember whether it was five or half past, but anyway - and then we did 'til one o'clock on Saturdays. Yes, six 'til one with a half hour breakfast. And anyway, it was well over - about fifty - fifty and a half or fifty two, I'm n
ot quite sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Would you have had holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Only - only the - on the public holi - the Bank - just the Bank Holidays, that's all. And that - that was three a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 When you were getting that ten shillings did you think it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
Didn't consider it at all. It was a job to go to and do it, that - that - that to be perfectly candid - was low enough - God knows, but still.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392620 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Did you give any of that to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 No - may have given her something now and again 
you know. But I don't know - well I must have given her something, I must have given her about five bob, half of it perhaps. 'Cos I - I never forget this. I was then - well on in my twenties. And therefore - I wanted things. And I was then beginning to br
anch out with me - as I told you before - came here, I knew nobody, I was in football and - dramatics society and - and of course that all absorbed what little - little pence - few pence I had.
