\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1141354 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 Yes. I - I - yes, I was - I was - after I finished - the war finished - I was discharged from the dockyard, I went
 over to Shorts. I went boat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1198299\charrsid2370612 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484140\charrsid2370612 
building there For a few weeks. And I went back in the dockyard again. I carried on in the for - for a while, few months, then I - wanted to go to - I wanted to get away, I wanted to go abroad for - to - emigrate really, althou
gh what we had in mind was me to get a knowledge - to get to Australia and get a knowledge of - that or New Zealand, didn't matter which, so I took a job as ships carpenter, on a ship that was lying in - in the dockyard at the time. She was a - under repa
i
r, she been a - a refugee ship brought over from Russian people, and - I took a job as ships carpenter, and when she - sailed on her crew I signed on, as ships carpenter. And I went to sea, and I went trooping out East, out to - down to France taking - wh
at's called colour troops from there to India, then around to Burma, repatriating Turkish prisoners from there to Constant - or Istanbul as it is now, and - and back again, backwards and forwards through the canal.
